# Hardening Lessons — Patterns That Break Tests

These rules come from iterative hardening runs. Every rule below caused real test
failures. Follow them or repeat the same mistakes.

---

## 1. SPA / Micro-Frontend Navigation

If your application is a **SPA with micro-frontends**, direct `page.goto('/route')`
may cause `net::ERR_ABORTED` because the browser tries to load the micro-frontend
before the SPA shell is ready.

**ALWAYS** navigate by clicking sidebar links or using in-app navigation, exactly
like a real user would:

```javascript
// WRONG — will ERR_ABORTED in SPA
await page.goto(baseURL + '/module/feature');

// CORRECT — sidebar navigation respects SPA routing
await this.nav.moduleLink.click();
await this.page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');
```

For modules without sidebar links, use `page.evaluate` to simulate link clicks:
```javascript
await page.evaluate((path) => {
  const a = document.createElement('a');
  a.href = path;
  document.body.appendChild(a);
  a.click();
  a.remove();
}, '/module/feature');
```

Or use `safeGoto()` which navigates via `window.location.href` assignment:
```javascript
async safeGoto(url) {
  await this.page.evaluate((u) => { window.location.href = u; }, url);
  await this.page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');
}
```

---

## 2. Launcher / Hub Pages

Some modules load a **hub/launcher page first**, not the sub-module directly.
The hub has navigation buttons; sub-module content only appears **after** clicking.

**NEVER** wait for sub-module elements on the hub page — they don't exist there.
**ALWAYS** wait for the hub title first, then click the correct navigation button.

---

## 3. Non-Deterministic Sidebar State

The sidebar can be expanded or collapsed when a test starts. Handle both states:

```javascript
await Promise.race([
  expandButton.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 }),
  collapseButton.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 15_000 }),
]).catch(() => {});
const needsExpand = await expandButton.isVisible().catch(() => false);
if (needsExpand) await expandButton.click();
```

**NEVER** assume the sidebar starts in a specific state.

---

## 4. NEVER Assume Locator Text — Verify Against Live DOM

Common locator assumption failures:

| What was assumed | What the DOM actually had |
|-----------------|--------------------------|
| `text=This Month` | `text=This Year` |
| `columnheader Name` | `columnheader Contact` |
| `button "List"` | `tab "List 518"` (role=tab) |
| `text=Open Items` | `text=Recent Items` |

**RULE**: Before writing any locator, obtain **ground truth** via:
1. Browser accessibility snapshot (preferred)
2. Error context from test failures
3. Dev repo source code (fallback — may differ from runtime)

**NEVER** guess column headers, metric card titles, or element roles.

---

## 5. Avoid `networkidle` in SPA Micro-Frontends

`page.waitForLoadState('networkidle')` blocks until no network activity for 500ms.
In SPAs, background requests (WebSockets, polling, lazy chunks) often **never** go
idle, causing indefinite timeouts.

```javascript
// DANGEROUS in SPA — can hang indefinitely
await page.waitForLoadState('networkidle');

// SAFE alternatives
await page.waitForLoadState('domcontentloaded');
await page.getByText('Expected Title').waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });
await this.smartWait(); // uses networkidle with .catch(() => {})
```

**RULE**: Never put `waitForPageReady()` (which uses networkidle) in spec `beforeEach`
hooks for SPA modules. Use `smartWait()` instead.

---

## 6. Prevent Strict Mode Violations Proactively

Playwright's strict mode fails when a locator matches multiple elements:

| Trap | Fix |
|------|-----|
| Generic heading text matches sidebar + page | Add `.first()` or scope to container |
| Shared text across modules | Use `{ exact: true }` |
| Hidden sidebar elements | Use specific text selector |
| Duplicate labels | Scope to `page.locator('main')` container |

**RULE**: When adding a text locator, always ask:
"Could this text appear anywhere else on the page?"
If yes, scope with `.first()`, `{ exact: true }`, or a parent container.

---

## 7. Timeout Calibration

Default Playwright timeout (30s) may be insufficient for lazy-loaded modules.

| Module type | Recommended timeout | Action timeout |
|-------------|-------------------|----------------|
| Heavy SPA modules | 60-90s | 15-20s |
| Standard pages | 30s (default) | default |
| Static/simple pages | 15s | default |

Set these in `playwright.config.js` per-project, NOT via `page.waitForTimeout()`.

---

## 8. Use Error Context for Forensic Diagnosis

When a test fails, Playwright can generate error context containing the
accessibility snapshot at the moment of failure.

**Diagnostic workflow**:
1. Read the error context / accessibility snapshot
2. Search for the expected element (by text, role, or partial name)
3. Compare what the DOM says vs what the Page Object assumes
4. Update the Page Object — keep the variable name, change only the selector

**NEVER** guess a fix without reading the error context or inspecting the live page.

---

## 9. Form Dialog Scoping

When creating items via modal/dialog forms, scope all field locators to the
dialog container. This prevents strict mode violations from background page
elements with the same labels.

```javascript
// WRONG — may match background elements
this.emailField = page.getByLabel('Email');

// CORRECT — scoped to dialog
this.formDialog = page.locator('[role="dialog"]');
this.emailField = this.formDialog.getByLabel('Email', { exact: true });
```

---

## 10. Table Row Identification

When verifying items in tables after CRUD operations:
- Use unique identifiers (email, full name, generated ID) — not common strings
- Add `.first()` to `rowByName()` calls to prevent strict mode on large tables
- Wait for table data to refresh after sort/filter operations using a polling loop
